2
00:00:04,320 --> 00:00:07,560
August 22nd, and here are today's top stories:

3
00:00:08,160 --> 00:00:13,260
Officials on the Hawaiian island of Maui have  released two more names of victims from the  

4
00:00:13,260 --> 00:00:19,620
historic blaze there two weeks ago. The death  toll stands at 115, up one from yesterday. 35  

5
00:00:19,620 --> 00:00:26,220
victims have been identified. At the same time,  more than 800 people on Maui remain unaccounted  

6
00:00:26,220 --> 00:00:30,900
for. The question is did they perish or have  they not checked in with family or friends?

7
00:00:30,900 --> 00:00:36,540
President Biden and First Lady Joe Biden toured  the wildfire devastation on Maui yesterday,  

8
00:00:36,540 --> 00:00:42,780
later pledging sustained federal support at a  community event at the Lahaina Civic Center.

9
00:00:43,320 --> 00:00:46,860
Hawaii Senator Mazie Hirono  says the loss is profound,  

10
00:00:46,860 --> 00:00:51,300
especially considering the modest  local government coffers on Maui:

11
00:00:51,300 --> 00:00:55,560
"It is going to be a lot of money, and  this county has suffered tremendous  

12
00:00:55,560 --> 00:01:02,340
losses — because their county budget  doesn't cover anything of this magnitude."

13
00:01:02,340 --> 00:01:05,940
The blaze on Maui was the  deadliest wildfire in U.S. history.

14
00:01:05,940 --> 00:01:11,340
Recovery efforts are underway in Southern  California in the aftermath of flash floods  

15
00:01:11,340 --> 00:01:18,360
and mudslides brought on by Tropical Storm Hilary.  From member station KVCR, Madison Aument reports:

16
00:01:18,360 --> 00:01:22,560
"The resort town of Palm Springs and  surrounding desert cities east of Los  

17
00:01:22,560 --> 00:01:27,000
Angeles received some three inches of  rain. The area typically sees roughly  

18
