The FDA has approved the first RSV vaccine to  be taken during pregnancy. The shot will protect  

26
00:02:07,020 --> 00:02:13,080
newborn babies during their vulnerable first  months of life. NPR's Sydney Lupkin has details:

27
00:02:13,080 --> 00:02:18,780
"The FDA has approved a new tool in the  arsenal against RSV. The virus causes mild,  

28
00:02:18,780 --> 00:02:20,280
cold-like symptoms in most people,  

29
00:02:20,280 --> 00:02:25,680
but can be serious in young children and older  adults. Pfizer studied the vaccine in more than  

30
00:02:26,280 --> 00:02:31,260
7,000 pregnant women across 18 countries.  The vaccine was 82% effective at preventing  

31
00:02:31,260 --> 00:02:36,180
severe disease in infants during their first  three months of life, and 70% effective in the  

32
00:02:36,180 --> 00:02:40,740
first six months. Dr. Scott Roberts, from the  Yale School of Medicine, says it's good news:

33
00:02:40,740 --> 00:02:46,440
'I think a lot of us in the medical community  are facing the winter ahead with some optimism  

34
00:02:46,440 --> 00:02:50,760
and enthusiasm that we now have several  options that are coming down the pipeline.'

35
00:02:50,760 --> 00:02:54,840
"Last month, the FDA also approved a  monoclonal antibody shot for babies  

36
00:02:54,840 --> 00:02:58,200
up to 24 months old. It's made by AstraZeneca.

37
00:02:58,200 --> 00:03:00,120
"Sydney Lupkin, NPR News."

